<!-- HERO -->
<div class="hero">
  <div class="hero-badge">Updated April 2026</div>
  <h1>K-1 Visa Medical Exam:<br>What to Expect, Costs & How to Prepare</h1>
  <p>The K-1 fiancé visa requires a medical exam by an embassy-approved panel physician before your interview. Here's exactly what happens — and how to pass it without surprises.</p>
  <div class="step-pills">
    <span class="step-pill">1. Book panel physician</span>
    <span class="step-pill highlight">→</span>
    <span class="step-pill">2. Physical + blood + X-ray</span>
    <span class="step-pill highlight">→</span>
    <span class="step-pill">3. Vaccinations</span>
    <span class="step-pill highlight">→</span>
    <span class="step-pill">4. Sealed envelope → embassy</span>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="content-wrap">
  <div class="main-col">

    <h2 id="overview">What Is the K-1 Visa Medical Exam?</h2>
    <p>The K-1 medical exam is a mandatory health screening required by U.S. immigration law before a fiancé visa can be issued. Its purpose is to identify conditions that make an applicant inadmissible to the United States under the Immigration and Nationality Act (INA § 212(a)(1)).</p>
    <p>The exam covers three main areas: <strong>physical health</strong>, <strong>communicable disease screening</strong>, and <strong>vaccination status</strong>. It is performed by a U.S. embassy-designated physician — called a <strong>panel physician</strong> — and the results are sent directly to the embassy in a sealed envelope. You bring that sealed envelope to your visa interview.</p>

    <div class="info-box">
      <div class="info-title">✓ Key Rule</div>
      <p>You <strong>cannot use your own doctor</strong>. The exam must be performed by an official panel physician designated by the U.S. embassy in your country. Find the list at your embassy's website or at <a href="https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/us-visas/visa-information-resources/find-medical-practitioner.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">travel.state.gov</a>.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 id="steps">The 4-Step Exam Process</h2>
    <div class="steps-grid">
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <div class="step-title">Find and book an official panel physician</div>
          <p class="step-desc">Go to your U.S. embassy's website and look for the list of approved panel physicians in your country. Book an appointment — some clinics are booked weeks in advance. Bring your passport and any vaccination records you already have.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <div class="step-title">Complete the physical examination</div>
          <p class="step-desc">The physician conducts a full physical: height, weight, vision, hearing, heart, lungs, skin, abdomen. They are looking for signs of communicable diseases and any condition that could affect admissibility. Blood tests and a chest X-ray are taken at the same visit or a follow-up appointment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <div class="step-title">Get required vaccinations (or document existing ones)</div>
          <p class="step-desc">The panel physician reviews your vaccination history. Any missing required vaccines are administered at the clinic. If you have records of prior vaccination, bring them — you may avoid repeat shots and extra cost. Blood titer tests can prove immunity for some vaccines.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="step-card">
        <div class="step-num">4</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <div class="step-title">Receive sealed medical packet — bring it to your interview</div>
          <p class="step-desc">The panel physician places your results in a sealed envelope addressed to the U.S. embassy. <strong>Do not open this envelope.</strong> Bring it intact to your visa interview. The consular officer opens it. If the envelope is opened or tampered with, you may need to redo the exam.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="whats-tested">What the Exam Tests</h2>
    <div class="tested-grid">
      <div class="tested-card">
        <div class="tested-header physical">🩺 Physical Examination</div>
        <div class="tested-body">
          <ul>
            <li>General appearance and vital signs</li>
            <li>Eyes, ears, nose, throat</li>
            <li>Heart and lung function</li>
            <li>Abdomen and lymph nodes</li>
            <li>Skin examination</li>
            <li>Neurological assessment</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tested-card">
        <div class="tested-header blood">🩸 Blood Tests</div>
        <div class="tested-body">
          <ul>
            <li>Syphilis (VDRL/RPR)</li>
            <li>Gonorrhea (in some countries)</li>
            <li>HIV (required for ages 15+)</li>
            <li>Hepatitis B surface antigen</li>
            <li>Additional STI screening per country</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tested-card">
        <div class="tested-header chest">🫁 Chest X-Ray</div>
        <div class="tested-body">
          <ul>
            <li>Required for applicants 15 years and older</li>
            <li>Screens for active tuberculosis (TB)</li>
            <li>If TB is suspected, additional sputum tests required</li>
            <li>Not required for pregnant applicants — TB skin test instead</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tested-card">
        <div class="tested-header mental">🧠 Mental Health Screening</div>
        <div class="tested-body">
          <ul>
            <li>Brief mental health assessment</li>
            <li>Screens for disorders associated with harmful behavior</li>
            <li>History of substance abuse or addiction</li>
            <li>Not a full psychiatric evaluation in most cases</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="tested-card">
        <div class="tested-header vaxx">💉 Vaccination Review</div>
        <div class="tested-body">
          <ul>
            <li>Review of all vaccination records</li>
            <li>Administration of missing required vaccines</li>
            <li>Documentation of immunity (titer tests if needed)</li>
            <li>All vaccines recorded on Form DS-2053</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="vaccinations">Required Vaccinations</h2>
    <p>The U.S. Department of State requires proof of all ACIP-recommended vaccinations. Missing vaccines are administered at the panel physician clinic — at your cost. If you already have vaccination records, bring them to potentially skip repeats.</p>

    <table class="vaxx-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Vaccine</th>
          <th>Status</th>
          <th>Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>MMR (Measles, Mumps, Rubella)</td>
          <td><span class="req-badge">Required</span></td>
          <td>2 doses; titer test can prove immunity</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Varicella (Chickenpox)</td>
          <td><span class="req-badge">Required</span></td>
          <td>2 doses; history of disease or titer can substitute</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Hepatitis A</td>
          <td><span class="req-badge">Required</span></td>
          <td>2-dose series; some countries accept 1 dose with pending 2nd</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Hepatitis B</td>
          <td><span class="req-badge">Required</span></td>
          <td>3-dose series; titer can prove immunity</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Tetanus / Tdap</td>
          <td><span class="req-badge">Required</span></td>
          <td>Tdap (with pertussis) once; Td booster every 10 years</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Influenza</td>
          <td><span class="req-badge">Required</span></td>
          <td>Annual; must be current season's vaccine</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Meningococcal (MenACWY)</td>
          <td><span class="req-badge">Required</span></td>
          <td>2 doses if first given before age 16</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Pneumococcal (PCV15 or PCV20)</td>
          <td><span class="req-badge">Required</span></td>
          <td>Schedule varies by age; required for all adults</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>COVID-19</td>
          <td><span class="req-badge">Required</span></td>
          <td>FDA-authorized or WHO EUL vaccine series required</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Polio (IPV)</td>
          <td><span class="age-badge">Age-based</span></td>
          <td>Required for children; adults assessed case-by-case</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>HPV</td>
          <td><span class="age-badge">Age-based</span></td>
          <td>Required up to age 26; recommended through age 45</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Rotavirus</td>
          <td><span class="age-badge">Age-based</span></td>
          <td>Infants only (2–6 months)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Zoster (shingles)</td>
          <td><span class="age-badge">Age-based</span></td>
          <td>Required age 50+; 2-dose Shingrix series</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <div class="warn-title">💡 Save money on vaccines</div>
      <p>If you already received some of these vaccines, bring your vaccination booklet or immunization records from your home country. Your panel physician may accept prior documentation or order a blood titer test to confirm immunity — potentially saving you the cost of repeat vaccines.</p>
    </div>

