    <h2 id="inadmissibility">Medical Conditions and Inadmissibility</h2>
    <p>Most people pass the medical exam without issues. However, certain conditions under INA § 212(a)(1) can make an applicant inadmissible. Understanding these categories helps you prepare.</p>

    <div class="inadmiss-grid">
      <div class="inadmiss-card red">
        <div class="inadmiss-label">🚫 Grounds for Inadmissibility</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-title">Communicable diseases of public health significance</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-desc">Active tuberculosis, syphilis (infectious stage), gonorrhea (infectious stage), and Hansen's disease (leprosy). <em>HIV is no longer on this list since 2010.</em></div>
      </div>
      <div class="inadmiss-card red">
        <div class="inadmiss-label">🚫 Grounds for Inadmissibility</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-title">Missing required vaccinations</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-desc">Failure to complete required vaccines without a valid medical exemption or religious objection. This is fixable — vaccines can be administered at the clinic.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="inadmiss-card orange">
        <div class="inadmiss-label">⚠ Case-by-Case Review</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-title">Physical or mental disorders with harmful behavior</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-desc">Only applies if the disorder is associated with past or current harmful behavior — not simply having a diagnosis. Mental health conditions alone are rarely grounds for denial.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="inadmiss-card orange">
        <div class="inadmiss-label">⚠ Case-by-Case Review</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-title">Drug addiction or abuse</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-desc">Current drug addiction is inadmissible. History of drug use without current addiction is reviewed case-by-case. Be honest — waivers are available in some situations.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="inadmiss-card green">
        <div class="inadmiss-label">✓ Not Grounds for Denial</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-title">HIV status</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-desc">HIV was removed from the communicable disease list in 2010. Being HIV-positive is not a ground of inadmissibility for immigration to the United States.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="inadmiss-card green">
        <div class="inadmiss-label">✓ Not Grounds for Denial</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-title">Chronic conditions and disabilities</div>
        <div class="inadmiss-desc">Diabetes, cancer, heart disease, physical disabilities, and most chronic conditions are not grounds for inadmissibility. The exam is not a general health filter.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="info-box">
      <div class="info-title">ℹ Waivers Are Available</div>
      <p>If you have a condition that is technically a ground of inadmissibility (such as active TB that is being treated), a <strong>waiver of inadmissibility (Form I-601)</strong> may be available. An immigration attorney can assess whether a waiver applies to your situation. Do not assume a condition means automatic denial.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 id="k1-vs-aos-exam">K-1 Exam vs. Adjustment of Status Exam: Two Separate Exams</h2>
    <p>Many couples are surprised to learn there are <strong>two separate medical exams</strong> in the K-1 process — one before the visa interview, and one after entering the U.S. when filing for Adjustment of Status (green card).</p>

    <div class="compare-box">
      <div class="compare-row header">
        <div class="compare-cell">Detail</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">K-1 Medical Exam</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">AOS Medical Exam (I-693)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">When performed</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">Before the visa interview, abroad</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">After entering U.S., before/during AOS filing</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">Who performs it</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">Embassy-designated panel physician</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">USCIS-designated civil surgeon in the U.S.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">Form used</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">DS-2053 (embassy-provided)</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">Form I-693 (sealed for USCIS)</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">Typical cost</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">$200–$600+ depending on country</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">$200–$500+ in the U.S.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">Vaccine records shared?</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">—</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">Civil surgeon may accept K-1 vaccine docs</div>
      </div>
      <div class="compare-row">
        <div class="compare-cell label">Validity</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">6 months from exam date</div>
        <div class="compare-cell">2 years (or until USCIS adjudicates)</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="timing">When to Schedule Your Medical Exam</h2>
    <p>Timing your medical exam correctly prevents two common problems: having results expire before your interview, or having to rush at the last minute.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Schedule after you receive your interview appointment date</strong> — NVC or the embassy will notify you of your interview date before you need the exam results</li>
      <li><strong>Exam results are valid for 6 months</strong> from the date of the exam — if your interview gets postponed past that window, you may need to redo parts of the exam</li>
      <li><strong>Book 4–6 weeks before your interview</strong> — this gives time for lab results to come back and the sealed envelope to be prepared</li>
      <li><strong>Don't wait until the week before</strong> — some panel physician clinics are booked weeks in advance, and blood test results can take 1–2 weeks</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="tips">7 Tips to Pass the First Time</h2>
    <div class="tips-grid">
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 01</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Find your vaccination records before the appointment</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">Dig up your childhood vaccination booklet. Even partial records can save you from repeat shots and extra cost at the panel physician clinic.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 02</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Get common vaccines at your local clinic first</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">For vaccines you know you're missing (flu shot, Tdap), getting them at your regular clinic first — and bringing the records — may be accepted, at a lower cost.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 03</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Don't open the sealed envelope — ever</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">The panel physician seals your results. An opened envelope means you may need to redo the entire exam. Bring it sealed to your interview; the consular officer opens it.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 04</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Be honest about medical history</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">The physician will ask about prior conditions, surgeries, mental health, and substance use. Honesty is essential — misrepresentation is a separate ground of inadmissibility and far more damaging than the condition itself.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 05</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Bring documentation for any managed condition</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">If you have a condition being actively treated (e.g., TB treatment, psychiatric medication), bring your doctor's letters and prescription records. Shows the condition is controlled, not a public health risk.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 06</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Don't schedule the exam too early</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">Results expire in 6 months. If your interview is 7 months away, wait. Redoing an expired exam is an avoidable cost of $200–$500+.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tip-card">
        <div class="tip-num">Tip 07</div>
        <div class="tip-title">Confirm the clinic's payment method in advance</div>
        <div class="tip-desc">Many panel physician clinics are cash only or have specific accepted payment methods. Call ahead so you're not stuck at the clinic with the wrong payment method.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">Who performs the K-1 visa medical exam?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Only a <strong>panel physician</strong> officially designated by the U.S. embassy in your country. You cannot use your personal doctor. Find the approved list on your embassy's website or at travel.state.gov.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">How much does the K-1 visa medical exam cost?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Costs vary widely by country — typically <strong>$200–$600+</strong> total, including the exam fee and any required vaccines. India and China tend to be on the lower end; Australia and the UK on the higher end. Bringing vaccination records can reduce costs.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">What vaccinations are required for the K-1 medical exam?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Required vaccines include MMR, varicella, hepatitis A, hepatitis B, Tdap, influenza, meningococcal, pneumococcal, and COVID-19. Age-based requirements apply to HPV, polio, rotavirus, and zoster. If you have prior vaccination records, the panel physician may accept them.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">How long is the K-1 visa medical exam valid?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>The results are valid for <strong>6 months</strong> from the exam date. Schedule your exam so that your embassy interview falls within this window. If your interview is delayed past 6 months, parts of the exam may need to be redone.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">Can a medical condition cause a K-1 visa denial?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes, but the list of disqualifying conditions is narrow: active communicable diseases (such as active TB or infectious syphilis), missing required vaccines, physical or mental disorders associated with harmful behavior, and drug addiction. HIV is <em>not</em> on the list since 2010. Waivers are available for some conditions.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-q">Do I need a second medical exam for Adjustment of Status?</p>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes. After entering the U.S. and marrying, you file for Adjustment of Status (I-485), which requires a separate medical exam using <strong>Form I-693</strong> from a USCIS-designated civil surgeon in the United States. This is a different exam from the K-1 panel physician exam — though some vaccine records may transfer.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

